    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-01T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-01T21:00:00-05:00" n="67"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d67">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.44 Chiang Kai-shek/117: Airgram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-02T09:00:00+07:00"
                            >August 2, 1943—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 20—5 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>A–22. There are persistent reports, largely from foreign news correspondents,
                    that Madame Chiang Kai-shek has returned to this country with something of an
                    anti-American bias. The principal basis for this alleged feeling on her part is
                    assumed to be that she did not as a result of her visit obtain from the American
                    Government all that she wanted or all that Mr. Willkie promised her. Other and
                    somewhat vague reasons ascribed are that because of some development or
                    developments in the United States during the latter part of her visit she
                    “realized” that she had overstayed her time and made one or two speeches too
                    many; also, that the unfortunate circumstances of her homecoming after a
                    hazardous and tiring journey during which she was airsick a great part of the
                    time (Embassy’s 1091, July 5, 10 a.m.<note n="95" xml:id="d67fn95">Not
                        printed.</note>) increased her sense of disappointment and frustration.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
